column50: •	The content and language objectives were written on the lesson plan and the content objective should be posted. The content objective seemed to be a long range goal. The content objective should detail what the students will know and be able to do at the conclusion of this lesson.  •	The lesson was standards-based. Also, Please write out the complete standards. CCSS.ELA-LITERACY.SL.9-10.1 CCSS.ELA-LITERACY.L.9-10.2 CCSS.ELA-LITERACY.L.9-10.4.A •	Students were assigned seats in table groups based on level and name of their pen pal.  The teacher posted the names of each student and the group they were in as the students entered. It would have been more efficient to have prepared the named of the students groups prior to the arrival of the students. During our debrief, the teacher stated that she did not have the time to do this. However, it was time consuming and the transition at the beginning of the period would have been smoother.  •	Teacher prepared a packet containing the 'Do Now', a reading, and tasks containing supports for the students. •	The 'Do Now' took 18 minutes which was too long. An effective 'Do Now' should last no more than 10 minutes. The teacher stated that it's not a big deal.  •	Teacher circulated, clarifying and assisting, as students worked.  •	Teacher elicited the meaning of various terms, pen pals and volunteers, as well as other words that came up in the reading.  •	The students will be writing letters to students in Indonesia. There was a missed opportunity to display a clear map showing Indonesia and the United States, /showing their relative locations. During our debrief, the teacher stated that she is sure they know where Indonesia is. However, we should be careful about assumptions. •	Teacher elicited the difference between formal/informal, volunteers and pen pals as they pertained to the lesson and task.  •	Teacher, modeled with class, a sample letter. Modeling is a powerful tool used by teachers that clarify expectations for the students.  •	References to a prior lesson were made. This was followed by the teacher modeling the second paragraph; questions students would like to a pen pal. Teacher referred to a prior lesson again on questioning; the use of 'what', 'where', 'when', 'why' and 'how'.  •	Teacher did a quick role-play with a student how to greet someone.  •	She explained about the agency that helps make the matches for student pen pals. Teacher explained that she will scan the letters and send them through the Internet.
column54: The classroom culture in one in which respect and caring is encouraged; teacher to student, student to teacher and student to student.  •	When teacher entered she posted the group members names on the board.  Preparing the names on chart paper prior to the class would have been more efficient as time would have been saved. •	Behavior was appropriate and teacher response to inappropriate behavior was consistent and respectful.
column58: •	While the teacher used some low-level questions, he or she posed questions to students designed to promote student thinking and understanding. However, the teacher should encourage students to respond to each other by asking students; who 'agree',' disagrees or 'has something to add' and having the students explain their thinking. •	The tasks were important to learn, but were not aligned with the Learning Objectives. Students did not introduce themselves to their new pen pal in writing.  they did not read about their new pen pals, they did not write 3-5 complete sentences describing themselves to a stranger,  they did not write 3-5 complete sentences describing themselves to a stranger in order to get to know one another. These were objectives for future lessons. It is important to make sure that the tasks/activities are reflective of the Learning Objectives. •	Student answers to questions throughout the period. •	Teacher closed by asking 3 students who didn't talk during the lesson why they feel they are doing this project. What do they feel they will learn from this unit. •	It is also a good idea to have something in writing to memorialize how students were assessed.
column60: •	Teacher has a generally accurate impression of a lesson's effectiveness and the extent to which instructional outcomes were met. However, there was much push back when recommendations were made.

column50: •	The lesson consisted of a content objective and language objective. The content objective, students will be able to identify figurative language through similes, metaphors and hyperboles was different from the content objective written in the lesson plan. The content objective written in the lesson plan was, SWBAT answer the reading comprehension questions by completing the guided notes. The language objective must be more than just reading a chapter. Students can discuss a question with a partner or they can write something dealing with chapter. •	The lesson was standards based: •	CCSS.ELA-Literacy.CCRA.R.2 – Determine central ideas or themes of a text and analyze their development; summarize the key supporting details and ideas.  •	CCSS.ELA-LITERACY.L.9-10.1-Demonstrate command of the conventions of standard English grammar and usage when writing or speaking.  •	CCSS.ELA-LITERACY.L.9-10.2 -Demonstrate command of the conventions of standard English capitalization, punctuation, and spelling when writing.  •	CCSS.ELA-LITERACY.L.9-10.6 -Acquire and use accurately general academic and domain-specific words and phrases, sufficient for reading, writing, speaking, and listening at the college and career readiness level; demonstrate independence in gathering vocabulary knowledge when considering a word or phrase important to comprehension or expression.  •	As students entered, the teacher handed the 'Do Now' to each student; what is a simile? Why do authors use similes?  •	Teacher compared and contrasted Similes and Metaphors; using examples.  •	Asked students for examples of each.  •	References to a prior lesson were made.  •	'Do Now' activity was timed.  •	Teacher circulated as students worked, clarifying and assisting.  •	Students were asked to find the 7 examples of figurative language from a reading.
column54: •	The classroom culture is a cognitively busy place where learning is valued by all with high expectations •	There is little loss of instructional time due to effective classroom routines and procedures. •	Student behavior was appropriate.
column58: •	  Students were asked to justify their responses.  •	  Some of the questions asked, were thought provoking and related to the story as demonstrated when the teacher asked the students if they think their life is pre determined or they make their own destiny.  This was followed by a share.  •	  Students were asked to make predictions and the teacher asked many questions. He then continued by stating that "This is what good readers do, they make predictions and ask questions." •	The teacher should encourage students to respond to each other by asking students; who 'agree',' disagrees or 'has something to add'.
column60: •	Teacher made an accurate assessment of a lesson's effectiveness and   cited general references to support the judgment. Teacher made a few specific suggestion of what could be tried another time the lesson is taught

column50: Re-teach/re-model the task multiple times using both L1 and English texts. Briefly, during Do Now, or if needed more time do it as your We Do activity. Learners need multiple exposures prior to understanding something so that they can start practicing and actively using it.Suggestions on additional differentiation for some students: on the pro's and con's T-chart ask for the exact number of evidence they need to list on each side. You can instruct them to find 3 pro's and 3 con's pieces of evidence and set the time of the activity. You can decide for more or fewer points depending how challenging the task is to be, but at least this gives them additional guidance of what they and/or how many pieces of evidence they need to find within the given time.
column54: There was a loss of instructional time between the model and guided/independent activities.

column50: •	The Learning Objective was written as an 'I can' statement. It is beneficial to write the learning objective in student friendly language by replacing SWBAT with 'I can'. 'I Can' statements empower students, provide a common focus, communicate what is important, build community and engagement and increase motivation and confidence.- Brian Shepard •	A content and language objective were included as per our discussion following the January observation. •	The lesson was standards-based: •	RI.6.2 - 8Determine a central idea of a text and how it is conveyed through particular details; provide a summary of the text distinct from personal opinions of judgments. •	RL.6.10 – 8 By the end of the year, read and comprehend literature, including stories, dramas and poems, in the grades 6 - 8 text complexity band proficiently, with scaffolding as needed at the high end of the range. •	All activities were timed.  •	This is an ICT with two 1-1 paraprofessionals. The co-teacher was not in attendance and the teacher told me that she arrives when she arrives since she lives in Pa.  •	As students worked on the 'Do Now', the teacher circulated making sure students were working.  •	Teacher posted the following: "Why is annotating important?" A student was called on to read and the teacher elaborated.  •	Teacher displayed the notation used for annotating text and verbally told the students which of the items they would concentrate on. Central Idea, Main Ideas, Text Structures, and Text Features were too numerous for the given period.  •	Students were given a text to read and given 6 minutes to complete the reading. Teacher circulated as students read. •	Students were also given an Annotating Nonfiction Rubric which the teacher displayed and read to the students.  •	Teacher modeled following a 'We do' strategy.  •	After completing the task with the class, the teacher had the students return to the rubric and grade her, the teacher.
column54: •	A student was removed at the beginning of class who was disrespectful to me. Removing students is not good practice as they could cause trouble in the hall and they are missing work.  Pulling them aside and contacting their home and/or guidance counselor would be more beneficial.  •	With regular guidance and prompting, students responded to the teacher as evidenced when the teacher stated, "If you can hear me clap once, if you can her me clap twice."  •	The teacher displays confidence and presence in the classroom.
column58: •	The 'Do Now' consisted of a painting followed by two questions: •	What do you see on the painting? •	What do you think is going on in the painting? Teacher allowed four students to share and she asked each of the students to respond to why? •	Most students called on were volunteers. Research for cold calling students show that the positives out weigh the negatives. Teachers against feel they don't want to make the student feel uncomfortable.  However, over time, this diminishes and, over time, students feel more comfortable participating in class discussions and, over time, more students answer questions voluntarily and, finally, teacher can call on students who she feels may be struggling. •	Students are compliant as opposed to engaged.  Students were totally quiet and copied their notes, as instructed. When students are engaged in learning, they are not merely "busy," nor are they only "on task." Rather, they are intellectually active in learning important and challenging content. •	Students were also given an Annotating Nonfiction Rubric which the teacher displayed and read to the students.  •	Teacher modeled using this rubric with the class. •	 A final summary question, related to the Learning Objective, should be asked even if time is running out. The teacher could stop the class and ask a    question, allow the students to discuss the or response with a partner followed with a share.  This question would give the teacher immediate feedback, in an informal way, whether the students understood the content.
column60: •	The teacher did not submit a reflection as requested. Reflecting on one's practice is necessary to grow professionally.

Instead of 'determine', it can be "Students will describe or explain ..." •	The lesson plan should be written using 'I can' format?  "I Can" statements empower students, provide a common focus, communicate what is important, build community and engagement and increase motivation and confidence.- Brian Shepard •	The standards addressed in the lesson should be noted in the lesson plan. •	After the 'Do Now', the teacher displayed two charts; one was a guide for answering short responses and the other was the meaning of each latter in RACE. (Restate, Answer, Cite evidence and Explain) •	The co-teacher modeled how to answer a short response question based on the description given by the teacher. As the co-teacher models, the teacher should be circulating and assisting the students without being disruptive.  •	After the co-teacher presented her piece, the teacher worked with a group of 6 students.  •	Teacher worked through a question using short response checklist.  •	The teacher asked the students to restate the central idea of lines 1-27.
column54: •	 There was little or no loss of instructional time due to effective classroom routines and procedures. •	Student behavior was appropriate.
column58: •	The teacher should try using the cold call strategy rather than accepting answers from students calling out. Those who call out responses, generally know the answer. Cold calling allows the teacher to call on students she feels may be struggling. Research for cold calling students show that the positives out weigh the negatives. Teachers against feel they don't want to make the student feel uncomfortable.  However, over time, this diminishes and, over time, students feel more comfortable participating in class discussions and, over time, more students answer questions voluntarily.  •	Students were engaged. •	The tasks were aligned with the Learning Objective. The teacher assessed the students various ways: •	Students were given a short response scoring rubric.  •	A final summary question was not included. A question is necessary in that it helps the teacher assess student understanding and inform instruction. This is true even for lessons that were not completed. The teacher must be aware of the time, stop the lesson, and assess student understanding by asking a question based on the content covered up to that point. •	Student work was collected.

column50: •	The Learning Objective was written as per the teacher's Assistant Principal's recommendation. However, to 'learn' the order of operations is not measurable. We can 'apply' the order of operations. •	The lesson was standards-based: •	Standards: 6..EE.A.2- Apply and extend previous understandings of arithmetic to algebraic expressions.  •	The 'Do Now' was on the board prior to the students' arrival.  •	The 'Do Now' was written in Spanish. Teacher and students spoke in both Spanish and English.  •	The 'Do Now' should take no more than 10 minutes. The 'Do Now' took 15 minutes  •	Students were called up to the board to write the answers to the 'Do Now' and the teacher debriefed the responses.  •	Teacher reviewed acceptable arithmetic notation. She elicited the different ways of writing the Product of w and 9.  •	Teacher displayed definitions of coefficient and variables in Spanish and English.  •	Care must be taken when giving definitions; the definition of exponent was given as "the amount of times a base is multiplied by itself". The correct definition is how many times the number is used as a factor. In addition, the definition of variable and coefficient were not mathematically accurate. They aspect of coefficient is that it is a constant and a variable changes.  •	Guided practice: teacher solved a problem with the class. Students were confused with 4c versus 4(c). Teacher explained that they represent the same operation. She could have referred to the last 'Do Now' problem that the class worked on.  •	The teacher showed a video. When showing a video, the teacher should pose a question the students should listen for in order to give the video a purpose. This would give the students an idea before they watch what to expect, what to look for and what might be worth thinking about. •	Teacher should plan for possible areas of confusion. Looking ahead, less than or is less than and more than and is more than may present challenges down the road. •	There should be a structured ending to the lesson.
column54: •	There was little loss of instructional time due to effective classroom routines and procedures •	The teacher displayed  confidence and presence in the classroom. •	Student behavior was appropriate.

This would give the teacher immediate feedback, in an informal way, whether the students understood the content and help guide planning for future instruction.

column50: •	The lesson was standards based:  CCSS.MATH.CONTENT.6.NS.C.6:Understand a rational number as a point on the number line. CCSS.MATH.CONTENT.6.NS.C.6.B: Understand signs of numbers in ordered pairs as indicating locations in quadrants of the coordinate plane; recognize that when two ordered pairs differ only by signs, the locations of the points are related by reflections across one or both axes. column50: •	The Learning Objective was written as an 'I can' statement. It is beneficial to write the learning objective in student friendly language by replacing SWBAT with 'I can'. column54: The classroom is cognitively busy with a variety of activities to support student learning. column58: Teacher uses a variety of questioning--both low and higher levels to promote student discussion.  He allows time for all students to answer and provides prompts as needed. column50: Teacher has good knowledge of content and pedagogy and has shown progress in building students' background and using their prior knowledge. column54: Teacher is highly committed to his students and works hard to convey this to his pupils. The students are still working on their role as learners. .  There is some loss of time if technology is not set up or fails during delivery of instruction. Also, if students come in late, they and the teacher play "catch up." Time is lost if this happens as it is a disruption to the flow and progression of the lesson in progress.  The teacher is very respectful of his students though implementation of standards of conduct appears to be inconsistent and there are times when student behavior is inappropriate.
column58: Teacher poses questions that appear to be too sophisticated and we are working on strategies to break down the linguistic and cognitive features into palatable comprehensible input and output.  In addition, the teacher is trying to stand back and allow free discussion with uneven results.  There are varying levels in this classroom and while the teacher attempts to involve all students, he is not always successful.  We have spoken about the need to use past learning and front loading vocabulary in scaffolding questions as well as the use of pictures and graphic organizers to "hook" students in. column50: Ms. Belgrade is teaching ICT Math, a subject area that is not her speciality, and is making a very good effort to master math concepts so that she can work well with her students.  She does not yet have the far-reaching understanding of math or teaching math that will allow her to create well-scaffolded units of study; she is also greatly limited by her co-teachers unwillingness to plan together and to design true co-teaching experiences that will increase learning outcomes for Ms. Belgrade's roster and for all the students in the class.
column54: Here again Ms. Belgrade is deeply limited by the co-teaching set-up.  She has many ideas for engaging students and setting up the classroom to have a more effective learning culture and environment, but she is somewhat powerless to make any decisions.  As such, the environment of the classroom was extremely unconducive to learning.  There is almost no culture of learning there, very few students showed respect to the teacher or to each other, and at any given moment only ¼ of the class was even trying to learn.  Most students were talking, playing on their phones or being disruptive in other ways for most of the lesson, with the exception of about ten minutes when most of the students were focused and copying the notes, if not actually understanding the problem on which they were working.
column58: Again, Ms. Belgrade seems to have a lot of potential and good ideas for discussion, student engagement and questioning but she has almost no opportunity for putting them into practice.  She did lead the lesson for fifteen minutes, and the rest of the time she focused on providing individual help, which was very effective for students who received it.  Her questioning techniques are at the developing level but against the chaos of this classroom, she seems to be trying to ask questions  that will engage students and get them to think more deeply.
column60: Quamina is very reflective of her practice and planning and open to suggestions and to trying ideas.  I saw some improvements since my first visit, and I can see that she is trying very hard to break through a very bad school culture and make a difference for her students.  Her potential is certainly being quashed at this school, and her principal is not even following the UFT teacher contract in designing her schedule, so I am very concerned about burn-out for her.

column12: Mozilla/5.0 (Macintosh; Intel Mac OS X 10_9_5) AppleWebKit/601.7.8 (KHTML, like Gecko) Version/9.1.3
column13: Mozilla/5.0 (Macintosh; Intel Mac OS X 10_9_5) AppleWebKit/601.7.8 (KHTML, like Gecko) Version/9.1.3 Safari/537.86.7
column50: Ms. Ruiz is teaching ICT Chemistry, a subject area that is not her specialty, and is making a very good effort to master chemistry concepts so that she can work well with her students.  She does not have the far-reaching understanding of chemistry that will allow her to create well-scaffolded units of study as far as content; but her understanding of how to reach SPED students and all students at different levels is advanced for a first year teacher.  However, she is greatly limited by her co-teachers unwillingness to plan together and to design true co-teaching experiences that will increase learning outcomes for Ms. Ruiz's roster and for all the students in the class.  As such, most of what Ms. Ruiz can do ends up in-class attempts to guide the co-teacher into approaches that will create differentiated learning experiences.  Ms. Ruiz's ideas are excellent, and she is able to plan very effectively for her self-contained science classes, but in this class she is forced to bandaid the problems because of the unwillingness of her co-teacher to follow the true purpose of co-teaching in an ICT classroom.
column54: In this area, Ms. Ruiz and her co-teacher could be excellent complements to each other, as their styles are very different and could work well together to reach different students.  However, again, her co-teacher is unwilling to follow any actual co-teaching model, does not plan with Ms. Ruiz and uses her mostly as a teaching assistant.  Students are very well-behaved, and actually it was remarkable to see students in this class with a completely opposite level of focus and engagement than I saw them having in a math class earlier that day with a different teacher.  But the co-teacher rules with the power of her personality and often makes cutting comments to students.  Ms. Ruiz's approach is much more student-centered, and she works to nurture students and bring out their natural desire to learn, but it is very difficult to build that classroom culture because she is being used as an assistant and not as a teacher.
column58: Again, in this area, Ms. Ruiz had a lot of excellent ideas, and I saw in the classroom that she tried to provide students with opportunities for deeper thinking, and that she noticed when students were not understanding concepts fully or needed more help, while her co-teacher moved on rapidly and did not notice.  In our post-ob, she shared with me ideas she had for differentiating the lesson, for increasing student engagement, but she was not able to put these into practice.  One student who had been a terror in the math class I observed earlier told me, when I asked her why she was so different in this class, that it was because of Ms. Ruiz, and I observed how Ms. Ruiz worked with this student very effectively and understood that this student needed to an LD assessment.  Ms. Ruiz also stopped the co-teacher several times to ask questions – in so doing, she modeled good questioning and deeper critical thinking and showed how she was able to gauge what students were struggling with – each time she asked those questions, she enabled a slow-down of the lesson, an attention to a skill that the students needed help with.  The echoes in the classroom were evidence that each time she did that, she was correct in understanding what the student's needed; and she was in her method making the best use of an ineffective co-teaching set-up.
column60: Ms. Ruiz is extremely reflective of her practice.  She is able to try out many of her ideas for honing her skills in her self-contained classroom and is very frustrated by her inability to do so in the other classrooms but is making the best of the situation.  She is so passionate and confident in her teaching ability that she may at times be more ready to share her ideas than to hear a new one, but given the virtual stranglehold on her in this set-up, and the total lack of support she receives from school administration – as well as the contract violations she is dealing with in terms of too many preps and not enough planning time, it is completely understandable that she is dying to share ideas for great teaching.

column50: •	The teacher is bright and does have a lot to offer but should realize that he is a co-teacher and should have an equal stance in the class. (see last bullet under comments for 2b, 2c and 2d.) •	The Learning Objectives were measurable but should be written in student friendly language using 'I Can' statements. 'I Can' statements empower students, provide a common focus, communicate what is important, build community and engagement and increase motivation and confidence.- Brian Shepard •	The Learning Objectives were too ambitious. •	The lesson was standards-based. Please write out the entire standard. •	There was no evidence of differentiation for groups of students. •	Physical environment must be conducive for students to work in groups. A case in point is the arrangement of the seats for discussion purposes, as we discussed. •	When assigning a text to read or watching a video, the teacher should pose a question the students should listen for in order to give the video a purpose. This would give the students an idea before they watch what to expect, what to look for and what might be worth thinking about. In the case of this text, the students could have been asked to think about how their assigned text impacted the American economy.  •	As students worked in the table groups, the teacher could have worked with one of the groups. •	While sitting in groups, the teacher should have had the students arrange their desks so they could participate more in a conversation.  •	There was some disagreement about the rating of the causes. Had the students been sitting in a circle or facing each other as the other groups were, they could have had a discussion and come to a consensus while the teacher facilitated.
column54: •	Transitions were smooth  •	Behavior was appropriate.  •	Students were well-behaved, motivated to take part in the lesson; yet teacher seems to exhibit a lack of presence. Students don't see the teacher as an equal as demonstrated when a student asked the co-teacher for his rankings of the causes.
column58: •	As the teacher elaborated, he could have asked thought provoking questions. An example could have been when Justin spoke about his grandfather's investment and the teacher mentioned that during the Great Depression was kind of like the opposite. This could have been presented to the students for discussion.  •	While the co-teacher facilitated the mini-lesson, the teacher elaborated and added information.  •	Keep class focused by staying a way from tangents and little jokes and stories. •	A final assessment question, related to the Learning Objectives, should have been asked at the end of the period. The students could have discussed it in their groups, followed by a share. After each group shared their priorities, the teacher could have asked what conclusions they can drw from the fact that different groups had different priority orders.

column60: Teacher makes a few specific suggestions of what could be tried another time the lesson is taught.

Some of the learning activities and materials are suitable to the instructional outcomes, and represent a moderate cognitive challenge, but with no differentiation for different students.
column54: The teacher conveys that with hard work students can be successful. There is little loss of instructional time due to effective classroom routines and procedures. Student behavior is generally appropriate.
column58: While the teacher may use some low-level questions, he or she poses questions to students designed to promote student thinking and understanding. The pacing of the lesson may not provide students the time needed to be intellectually engaged. Assessment is regularly used during instruction, through monitoring of progress of learning by teacher.
column60: Teacher makes an accurate assessment of a lesson's effectiveness and the extent to which it achieved its instructional outcomes and can cite general references to support the judgment.

column54: With regular guidance and prompting, students follow established routines. Standards of conduct appear to have been established.
column58: Assessment is used sporadically to support instruction, through some monitoring of progress of learning by teacher and/or students. Teacher attempts to engage all students in the discussion and to encourage them to respond to one another, with uneven results.

column50: During this triple period, students engaged in a vocabulary building exercise that allowed them to consider activities done at different times of day.  Mr. Ruggerio was aware of the different levels of the students and in one-on-one circulation during the exercise, he was able to offer level-appropriate help.  He also made some use of visual learning in the form of notes on the smartboard.  There was no differentiation in the design of the exercise itself, however and students were asking the same questions again and again without thinking deeply or trying out the same construction  to identify other things they might do on any given day.  Later students worked on a long-term project, "The Best Day Ever."  Students were able to create narratives, and they were asked to add visuals to this project; Mr. Ruggerio allowed for the fact that students were at very different points as far as completion.   But there was not much opportunity for higher-order or creative thinking; and most students were writing about very quotidian events and were unable to say why their narratives were about the "best day ever."  They were also downloading stock images from the internet instead of drawing something specific to their own lives or using personal photographs.
column54: Mr. Ruggerio's classroom has a strong learning culture.  Students are respectful of him and of each other, and they enjoy being there and are focused and engaged.  It's clear that he knows his students and cares about them.  Changes in lesson structure to elicit higher order thinking and more creativity will allow for even better engagement and higher learning outcomes.
column58: Again, changes in lesson structure to elicit higher order thinking and more creativity will allow for even better engagement and higher learning outcomes.   Mr. Ruggerio does ask many good questions and is able to validate even responses that are not always what he was looking for.  He is not always using questioning as a gauge for understanding exactly how students are or are not grasping concepts, and some better use of questioning techniques will allow him to gauge this better.  The worksheets prepared are solid but don't allow for much higher order thinking or creative work, which is potentially stunting student engagement.  I also would recommend some use of mastery in native languages to help students think more deeply at the same time that they are acquiring new language skills in English.
column60: Mr. Ruggerio always seems open to suggestions and eager to reflect on his teaching practice.  He is, like most teaching fellows, overwhelmed by having to teach, go to school and have a family life and a long commute, so he does not always have time for serious reflection on his practice.

column12: Mozilla/5.0 (Macintosh; Intel Mac OS X 10_9_5) AppleWebKit/601.7.8 (KHTML, like Gecko) Version/9.1.3
column13: Mozilla/5.0 (Macintosh; Intel Mac OS X 10_9_5) AppleWebKit/601.7.8 (KHTML, like Gecko) Version/9.1.3 Safari/537.86.7
column50: Ms. Cervantes works in a co-teaching setting but is not given the opportunity to participate in planning or to do any style of co-teaching except assisting.  She is given lesson plans and readings to modify for her students and has worked very hard to create separate readings.  But as students are already allowed to choose between four different reading levels for tasks, I suggested she use that time instead to create differentiated versions of the activities and tasks.  She works effectively one-on-one with students during class time, but is in effect creating a pull-out each time rather than really using the model for push-in.  We are trying to work within the very tight parameters set by her co-teacher.
column54: Again, the classroom culture and procedures are being determined almost completely by the co-teacher into whose classroom Ms. Cervantes pushes.  Ms. Cervantes has good relationships with students, they seem to respect her and to enjoy working with her.  She expresses care and concern and shows her belief in the students on her roster and any students with whom she works.   Were she able to work within a more effective co-teaching model, it would be easier to assess her abilities in this index, and I believe we would see an increase in engagement for all students.  But this has so far not been possible at this school.
column58: Again, in this area, Ms. Cervantes is following the lead of the co-teacher and is given very little opportunity to innovate for differentiation.   Students in this class spend a lot of time looking at rubrics, skills sets, identifying what they are about to do and what skills it will help them develop, and gauging their own achievements as they go.  So much time is spent on this, in fact, that once students are actually able to settle down to read content or to use it to fill out the "note catchers," they are extremely rushed and have very little time to think deeply.  I observed many conversations spring out of the reading that showed deep interest and which were at a much higher order of thinking, but which were quashed by the co-teacher because students were not focusing on the lower-order questions on the notecatcher.  Ms. Cervantes has not demonstrated an ability to bring students to this higher order, but it is hard to assess her in this area since she is not given the chance to do this either.
column60: Ms. Cervantes is very eager for feedback and wants to grow as a teacher.  She is often in a state of anxiety about feedback and/or about limits set on her or feelings that she is not "good enough." It's also hard for me to tell if she is further limited by her own anxiety or perhaps if the co-teacher is limiting her participation in planning and lesson leading because of teaching skills issues.

column12: Mozilla/5.0 (Macintosh; Intel Mac OS X 10_9_5) AppleWebKit/601.7.8 (KHTML, like Gecko) Version/9.1.3
column13: Mozilla/5.0 (Macintosh; Intel Mac OS X 10_9_5) AppleWebKit/601.7.8 (KHTML, like Gecko) Version/9.1.3 Safari/537.86.7
column50: Ms. Abasi's lesson focused on teaching students word mapping as a note taking skill; the content covered was culture – American, her own, students'.  There was some scaffolding in the lesson, and she chose a topic that would be relevant to this population of entirely immigrant students.  Using her own life as a model took up too much of the lesson, and it became unclear if her main goal was to teach mapping or to have students think about their own culture.  Students were able to work with the mapping but not master it, and I did not see much higher order thinking or opportunities for creativity.  Allowing students to do some brainstorming in their own language for application to the lesson in English would have allowed for greater engagement and mastery of ideas before mastery of the mapping skill.
column54: Ms. Abasi's clearly respects her students, and vice versa.  She also clearly knows their skills and their family backgrounds to some degree, and she makes use of that knowledge to reach her students during the lesson.  I did not observe differentiation in lesson planning to reach different students in different ways – particularly at the lowest and highest end of language skills.   She has a good presence in the classroom and as such does not have any serious discipline problems, but nor does she have high levels of self-motivated learning, creative thinking, etc.  Her approach is still fairly teacher-centered but by force of her personality and her love/respect for the students, a culture of learning is still developing.
column58: Here again,  I did not observe differentiation in questioning technique or other modes of engagement/assessment to reach different students in different ways – particularly at the lowest and highest end of language skills.  Most of the class is being mediated through her, and opportunities for students to work together are not highly structured for positive interdependence.  Her approach is still fairly teacher-centered but she has great focus and good ideas for how to help her students acquire language skills.
column60: Ms. Abasi is able to reflect on her lesson and is open to suggestions.  At times she will focus more on explaining her choice than on assessing how effective it was, and like many new teachers, she sometimes sets too broad a focus for the objectives, leading to some issues in planning/execution.   She is developing the ability to be reflective about this.

column50: Mr. Acree's lesson used a reading of a short story "The Monkey's Paw," and follow-up questions; his stated goal was to prepare students to understand the elements of story in order to write their own stories.  However, students across an extremely wide range of skills all had the same story and the same questions.  Some students had barely started the questions while others had almost finished; but there was not a clear task for students who needed to move on or an adjustment for students who were really struggling.  I did not observe anything in the lesson that asked students to begin thinking about how to create their own stories with this story as a model for either form or content.   Mr. Acree had worked hard to find a story at his students' reading level but had not considered the need for a higher interest content that would engage them more deeply, or for tasks that would do so. ESL skills were addressed with vocabuarly and grammar questions but  not with high interest, higher-level thinking activities.
column54: Mr. Acree has a good sense of keeping order in the classroom and students seem to respect him and his rules.  But he is relying more on rules and procedures than on engagement through the lesson itself.  Students are working more because they have to than because there is a sense of joy and excitement for the learning.  Most of this lesson was individual work with very little opportunity for interaction or sharing; and for most of the lesson, students were just working on computers.  Side conversations even on topic were discouraged.  I commented to Mr. Acree that he was clearly working hard to create the materials for the lesson and that he really cared about his students' learning and wanted to help them acquire skills, but that he did not seem to be happy to be in the classroom or to be showing them how much he cared.  More often he seemed annoyed or ready to pounce on any loss of focus.
column58: This lesson involved mostly individual work.  Mr. Acree worked hard to create the packets and the computer document they used to answer the questions, and he tried to create readings and questions that were on skill-level.  The questions as written were a gauge of their reading comprehension but did not require higher order thinking or ask them to think about the craft of writing despite that being a stated objective.  There was very little discussion except some more procedural discussion at the start of the class, so not much opportunity to observe questioning techniques other than for written questions.
column60: Mr. Acree does seem open to discussion and eager for ideas.  He was particularly eager for assistance finding high-interest readings for his students' skills level.  He understood my analysis of the lesson as far as it not achieving its stated objective, though he had not seen that before we discussed it, and seemed open for ideas as to how to better focus it.

column12: Mozilla/5.0 (Macintosh; Intel Mac OS X 10_9_5) AppleWebKit/601.7.8 (KHTML, like Gecko) Version/9.1.3
column13: Mozilla/5.0 (Macintosh; Intel Mac OS X 10_9_5) AppleWebKit/601.7.8 (KHTML, like Gecko) Version/9.1.3 Safari/537.86.7
column50: Ms. Gjoza's lesson was a Regents review.  There was very limited observable lesson structure; rather students were asked a couple of questions about the work they had done previously, they were shown a description of a Regents essay writing skill and then each student worked on his/her own for the rest of the period on a practice Regents question.  Students came in late and left early.  Some students used their phones throughout the period; one student watched the Trump inauguration while working on her essay.  Ms. Gjoza and her co-teacher worked one-on-one with the students; but her co-teacher engaged in quite a lot of side conversation with the students so that the period seemed more like a study hall or a homework help session than a planned lesson within a scaffolded unit.  Ms. Gjoza did seem to know each student's skill level and what s/he needed most but needed support as far as how to help them move to a higher level as far as Regents test readiness.
column54: Previous lessons I observed were stronger than this one; but in general in this lesson and those, Ms. Gjoza has a strong presence in the classroom.   She is respected and shows respect for her students.  The school culture at this school is very hard to overcome; students come and go from classrooms, late and early, with no consequences.  They are often absent and unable to follow any unit trajectory as a result.  They openly use their phones, chat, eat, etc.  Ms. Gjoza is frustrated with this aspect of the school culture but feels powerless to make her classroom follow a higher standard.  Students are also older, most with jobs and some aspect of an adult life, so in that way as well, Ms. Gjoza feels limited.  She does not have extreme behavioral disruptions, but there are constant pressures on the flow of the class that undermine the learning culture.   She has instituted many well-thought-out strategies for creating procedures to overcome many of the school's limitations; these are used to varying degrees of success.
column58: Again, I have observed other lessons in Ms. Gjoza's classroom that were much stronger in this area; but in this particular lesson there was very little assessment or potential for using questions as a learning tool.  Ms. Gjoza did seem to know each student's skill level and what s/he needed most but was uncertain of how to help them move to a higher level as far as Regents test readiness.  Presumably she was able to assess students informally by working with them one-on-one during the lesson.
column60: During this year, I have found Ms. Gjoza to be reflective of her own practice.  For this lesson, she was surprised at my assessment and did not seem to be aware of the many areas in which the lesson needed structure and accountability for both teachers and students.

column12: Mozilla/5.0 (Macintosh; Intel Mac OS X 10_9_5) AppleWebKit/601.7.8 (KHTML, like Gecko) Version/9.1.3
column13: Mozilla/5.0 (Macintosh; Intel Mac OS X 10_9_5) AppleWebKit/601.7.8 (KHTML, like Gecko) Version/9.1.3 Safari/537.86.7
column50: Mr. Billson's knowledge of history was excellent, and he was able to put together a reading very quickly when he discovered upon arrival to the class that his co-teacher had not shown up for work nor notified him.  However, the lesson itself had very little structure to it, and no accountability for students.  They had a worksheet to fill out but he had not planned for how to translate that work into a coherent discussions, and students did not understand how they would be assessed, or for what.
column54: Many teachers in better circumstances appear to be overwhelmed, disgruntled, annoyed.  But Mr. Billson in a very chaotic classroom environment continued to be cheerful and happy to see and work with his students.   That will serve him sell as he hones his other teaching skills.  But the learning environment for this lesson was disastrous.  Students were extremely rude to him and to each other.  One group of students chatted, played on their phones and ate a full meal during the lesson, almost never participating.  One small group of students did participate, but inconsistently, clearly aware that there were no consequences for not participating and no reward for participating.  There was no clear outcome nor a clear end assessment or connection to homework.  Mr. Billson mentioned that his co-teacher does not plan with him or give him an opportunity to truly co-teach; the absence of the co-teacher did not change the problem, that Mr. Billson had not been able to create a learning environment through a strong lesson plan or established procedures.
column58: Again, Mr. Billson had made an effort to find an interesting reading for students to do when the co-teacher did not show up and had not left a lesson.  And he had a good idea for how students could relate the despotic leader in the reading to studies of other despotic leaders.  But there student engagement was extremely inconsistent and not purposeful, there was little opportunity for solid discussion, including questioning, and while he did not have wild behavior in the room, nor did he have focus or respect from students.  Even a purposeful arrangement of the chairs in the room, with students sitting together for discussion and with the chatty students separated, would have made a huge difference.
column60: Mr. Billson is in the very early stages of being able to reflect on the lesson.  Once he has attained more skills in pedagogic methods, he will have more tools for reflecting on practice as well.  But he is open to suggestions and eager to improve.

column12: Mozilla/5.0 (Macintosh; Intel Mac OS X 10_9_5) AppleWebKit/601.7.8 (KHTML, like Gecko) Version/9.1.3
column13: Mozilla/5.0 (Macintosh; Intel Mac OS X 10_9_5) AppleWebKit/601.7.8 (KHTML, like Gecko) Version/9.1.3 Safari/537.86.7
column50: Ms. Ruiz understood the math concepts she was teaching very well.  She was not yet able to predict where and how students would struggle with those concepts.  For example, she did not realize that most students did not understand the term "bisect" or what the intersection of the diagonals looked like as far as being perpendicular.  So she taught this concept quickly without realizing that could not apply the rule because they didn't understand the terms fully.  The lesson had some practice and discussion of the practice but the rest of the lesson involved students working alone on a worksheet.  They were told they could work together "after a little while," but there was no structure for that cooperative learning.  There was little time for sharing answers or process and no closure beyond a basic exit ticket.
column54: Ms. Ruiz had few discipline problems.  She was respectful of her students and demanded focus and respect.  But she had only six students in the classroom, and there was not a high level of engagement.  Her students were motivated to learn math, and they focused for much of the lesson for that reason only.  But there was not a lot of intrinsic engagement in the lesson structure; and with a larger group of students, that lack of engagement would become problems in discipline.
column58: Ms. Ruiz had some procedures in place for assessment at the beginning and end of the lesson, including a Do Now and an exit ticket, as well as homework and a worksheet.  These allowed her to assess when she was going over papers.  She did not create many opportunities for students to engage in the material through discussion, questions, explanations, etc., and as such I did not observe a lot of assessment opportunities during the lesson.  She did ask questions during the mini-lesson but these did not require higher order critical thinking for the most part.
column60: Ms. Ruiz is eager to learn techniques that will help her increase student engagement and learning outcomes.  She is beginning to learn skills that will help her self-assess but she is open to suggestions and eager to grow.

column12: Mozilla/5.0 (Macintosh; Intel Mac OS X 10_9_5) AppleWebKit/601.7.8 (KHTML, like Gecko) Version/9.1.3

column50: Mr. Fisher-Smith co-taught this math lesson.  His co-teacher was not hostile to his participation in planning and execution but nor was she open to a true co-teaching relationship.  Mr. Fisher-Smith was aware of some but not all the needs of the students on his roster; but had not created many modifcations for them or  for other students who might need his help.  He circulated throughout the lesson and was able to adjust his questions and mode of assistance based on what he knew each student needed.  But I did not observe planning or execution that seemed to really address individual students' IEP's or the students who were in general ed.
column54: Mr. Fisher-Smith and his co-teacher had some strong classroom procedures in place, including using popsicle sticks with numbers on them to ensure that students participated even when not called upon.  Students were for the most part focused and wanted to complete the worksheet.  And when students went to the board to do a problem, the other students were used to discussing each step and deciding when the work was correct and when it was not.  But there was not a sense of a learning culture where students took active responsibility for learning.  Other than the moments when students went to the board to do problems and other students commented, the work was largely just students going one by one through a worksheet.  Students used calculators even for the simplest of operations.
column58: Mr. Fisher-Smith was more of an assistant during the lesson, so I was not able to observe a lot of questioning as a tool for assessment.  But in his one-on-one work with students, he did ask questions to guide students to solve problems and to think through each step.   Students were engaged more because they wanted to learn the math than because the work provided was designed to engage them.  There were few structured opportunities for positive interdependence, and even the use of numbers on sticks instead of names contributed to a feeling that this was many students learning math at the same time, rather than a community of learners coming together for a common goal.
column60: Mr. Fisher-Smith is very open to suggestions and eager to learn techniques, skills, etc.  He is reflective of his practice, though at an early stage of being able to assess a lesson's structure.  He is at an early stage also of being able to understand how he can co-plan to ensure that his roster of students is being served according to their IEP's.

column50: Ms. Smith's designed a template for students to use in undertaking the first stages of research on topics they had picked either in Global Studies or just as a general topic of interest.  The connection to the Global class was unclear; Ms. Smith did not actually know if students could use their work in her class for Global Studies, or how deeply connected her class had to be. This seemed to be more a result of poor support from her department, as Ms. Smith was very eager to find a solution and to create meaningful lessons.  The lesson structure itself did not make use of positive interdependence or clearly define how much students had to accomplish during the period, or how they would be assessed.  The connection to homework or the next day's lesson was unclear; but students did understand that this was a step in a unit that would lead to a research paper.
column54: Ms. Smith is very overwhelmed by the school culture and uncertain of how to establish a real classroom community.  Students were unfocused and unengaged, and Ms. Smith felt overwhelmed by too many preps and teaching assignments in content areas in which she felt weak.  Her frustration was evident in the classroom and exacerbated issues of management and weak classroom community connections.  We discussed ways for her to work with students to define student responsibility and to make them active participants in learning.
column58: Ms. Smith created a worksheet for students to help them focus their research but there was no differentiation for varying skills and needs.  All students had the same work no matter their topic or IEP.  There was some engagement as some students were able to pick topics, but others had been assigned topics and most did not know how to undertake research in a meaningful way. Many students were distracted or unfocused, and Ms. Smith spent a lot of the class asking them to focus without seeing that the lesson didn't offer them enough structure or high-interest content.
column60: Ms. Smith was very open to suggestions and was in fact desperate for them.  Her school supervisor has not been supportive and she feels very lost and overwhelmed.  She was able to see many of the issues with the outcome of the lesson but was not yet able to understand what was causing poor outcomes.  We discussed strategies and I encouraged her to develop her own teaching voice and meet the students where they are, while giving them the chance to create the rules, consequences and rewards for the learning community.
